Machine Learning Projekt - Olympiade¶

Einleitung¶

The Olympic Games are a worldwide sporting event, at which the best athletes in the world compete in various disciplines on behalf of their country. Its origins go back to ancient Greece.

We want to create a learner who can predict the medal winners at the next Olympic Games based on the current health, economic and educational situation of all participating countries.

With the help of such a learner one could support experts in estimating the probability of winning in individual countries and one could dispense with possible oracles such as those used at the Football World Cup.

Datasets¶

We are using 2 different datasets.

The First is about the medalwinners of the last years

https://www.kaggle.com/heesoo37/120-years-of-olympic-history-athletes-and-results

and the other is about life expectancy of all countries

https://www.kaggle.com/kumarajarshi/life-expectancy-who

Objectives and Procedure¶

To build a maschine learner, we...

  • merge the datasets.
  • clean the resultet data
  • do a exploratory data analysis
  • preprozess our data
  • build a random forest classifier
  • validate the random forest classifier
  • build a adaboost classifier out of the random forest
  • validate the bosted classifier
  • build a K-Nearest neigthbour classifier
  • validate the K-Nearest neigthbour classifer
  • build a voting classifier
  • validate the voting classifier
  • swiss medals 2020
  • conclusion

#DeepCopy list
olympicGames = cp.copy(athlete_events)

# Builds Medalcount for the events
olympicGames['MedalCount'] = np.where(olympicGames['Medal'].isna(),0,1)
olympicMedals = pd.pivot_table(olympicGames,
                               index = ['Team', 'Year', 'Event'],
                               columns = 'Medal',
                               values = 'MedalCount',
                               aggfunc = np.sum,
                               fill_value = 0).reset_index()

# Teamevents with multible Medals count as 1 Medal
olympicMedals.loc[:,'Gold'] = np.where(olympicMedals['Gold']>=1,1,0)
olympicMedals.loc[:,'Silver'] = np.where(olympicMedals['Silver']>=1,1,0)
olympicMedals.loc[:,'Bronze'] = np.where(olympicMedals['Bronze']>=1,1,0)

# Cleans different Country writings like (Switzerland-1)
i=0
for team in olympicMedals['Team']:
    if team.endswith('-',-2,-1):                 # Finds a - as second last element
        olympicMedals.loc[i,'Team'] = team[:-2]   # Delets last two elements Bsp. -1
    i = i+1

# Builds Medalian count
medalTable = olympicMedals.groupby(['Year', 'Team'])['Gold','Silver','Bronze'].sum().reset_index()
medalTable['Medals'] = medalTable['Gold']+medalTable['Silver']+medalTable['Bronze']
medalTableAfter2000 = medalTable[medalTable['Year']>=2000]

# Fixes some different country name writings
lifeExpectancy.loc[:,'Country'] = np.where(lifeExpectancy['Country']=='UnitedKingdomofGreatBritainandNorthernIreland',
                                           'Great Britain',lifeExpectancy['Country'])
lifeExpectancy.loc[:,'Country'] = np.where(lifeExpectancy['Country']=='UnitedStatesofAmerica'

                                           'Macedonia',lifeExpectancy['Country'])
lifeExpectancy.loc[:,'Country'] = np.where(lifeExpectancy['Country']=='Venezuela(BolivarianRepublicof)',

lifeExpectancy.loc[:,'Country'] = np.where(lifeExpectancy['Country']=="Côted'Ivoire",

Possible Features¶

  • Country: Country Name
  • Year: Year
  • Status: Developing or not Developing
  • Life expectancy: Life Expectany in Age
  • Adult Mortality: Adult Mortality Rates of both sexes (probability of dying between 15 and 60 years per 1000 population)
  • infant deaths: Number of Infant Deaths per 1000 population
  • Alcohol: Alcohol, recorded per capita (15+) consumption (in litres of pure alcohol)
  • percentage expend: Expenditure on health as a percentage of Gross Domestic Product per capita(%)
  • Hepatitis B: Hepatitis B (HepB) immunization coverage among 1-year-olds (%)
  • Measles: Measles - number of reported cases per 1000 population
  • BMI: Average Body Mass Index of entire population
  • under-five deaths: Number of under-five deaths per 1000 population
  • Polio: Polio (Pol3) immunization coverage among 1-year-olds (%)
  • Total expenditure: General government expenditure on health as a percentage of total government expenditure (%)
  • Diphtheria: Diphtheria tetanus toxoid and pertussis (DTP3) immunization coverage among 1-year-olds (%)
  • HIV/Aids: Deaths per 1 000 live births HIV/AIDS (0-4 years)
  • GDP: Gross Domestic Product per capita (in USD)
  • Population: Population of the country
  • thinness 1-19: Prevalence of thinness among children and adolescents for Age 10 to 19 (%)
  • thinnes 5-9: Prevalence of thinness among children for Age 5 to 9(%)

Used Features¶

  • Country: Country Name (nominale)
  • Year: Year (kontinuierlich)
  • Developing: Developing or not Developing (ordinale)
  • Life expectancy: Life Expectany in Age (diskrete)
  • Adult Mortality: Adult Mortality Rates of both sexes (probability of dying between 15 and 60 years per 1000 population) (kontinuierlich)
  • infant deaths: Number of Infant Deaths per 1000 population (kontinuierlich)
  • Alcohol: Alcohol, recorded per capita (15+) consumption (in litres of pure alcohol) (diskret)
  • BMI: Average Body Mass Index of entire population (diskret)
  • Total expenditure: General government expenditure on health as a percentage of total government expenditure (%) (kontinuierlich)
  • GDP: Gross Domestic Product per capita (in USD) (diskret)
  • Population: Population of the country (diskret)

Preprozessing¶

In [38]:
#Deep Copy
cleanedData = cp.copy(olympicLifeCleaned)

#Drop Gold Silver Bronze Medallion
cleanedData = cleanedData.drop('Gold', axis=1)
cleanedData = cleanedData.drop('Silver', axis=1)
cleanedData = cleanedData.drop('Bronze', axis=1)
cleanedData = cleanedData.drop('Year', axis=1)

#Encode Country Strings
le = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
cleanedData['Country'] = le.fit_transform(cleanedData['Country'])

#group by Country
#groupedData = cleanedData.groupby("Country").mean().round(0).astype('int')

#generate feature frame
X = cleanedData.drop('Medals', axis=1)
Y = cleanedData['Medals']

# Splits the Medalcount in groups 0/1-25/26-50/51-75/76-100/+100
df = pd.DataFrame(Y, columns=['Medals'])
for index, row in df.iterrows():
    if df.loc[index,'Medals'] == 0:
            df.loc[index,'Medals'] = 0
    elif df.loc[index,'Medals'] >= 1 and df.loc[index,'Medals'] <= 25:
            df.loc[index,'Medals'] = 1
    elif df.loc[index,'Medals'] >= 26 and df.loc[index,'Medals'] <= 50:
            df.loc[index,'Medals'] = 2
    elif df.loc[index,'Medals'] >= 51 and df.loc[index,'Medals'] <= 75:
            df.loc[index,'Medals'] = 3
    elif df.loc[index,'Medals'] >= 76 and df.loc[index,'Medals'] <= 100:
            df.loc[index,'Medals'] = 4
    elif df.loc[index,'Medals'] >= 101:
            df.loc[index,'Medals'] = 5
            
Y= df['Medals']
df = df.sort_values(['Medals'])

#Split data in 70% learn and 30% test data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.30, random_state=0)

Random Forest¶

The Random Forest Classifier is a supervised learning algorithm. It uses multiple descicion trees so create the best.

We decided to use the random forest classification because it is quite easy to implement and well suited for our dataset.

Creating and Training¶

ADA-Boost¶

AdaBoost takes a weaker Classfifier (in this case random Forest), and trains it sequencell to accieve a better result with weighting.

Creating and Training¶

KNN LEARNER¶

The KNN algorithm (k-nearest neighbors) is an easy to implement, supervised algorithm for machine learning. The KNN algorithm is based on the assumption that similar things exist in close proximity. In short, similar things are close to each other.

We decided to use the kNN classification because it is quite easy to implement and well suited for our dataset. The dataset is not too big and has only two dimensions.

Find best K¶

To Find the best K we start with a random k. In this case 5.

crossAccuracyList = []
accuracyList = []


# Calculating error for K values between 1 and 40
for i in range(1, 40):  
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=i)
    knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_knn_pred_train = cross_val_predict(knn, X_train, y_train, cv=7)
    y_knn_pred_test = knn.predict(X_test)
    crossAccuracyList.append(accuracy_score(y_train, y_knn_pred_train))
    accuracyList.append(accuracy_score(y_train, y_knn_pred_train))

    
figure = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

Voting¶

Voting improve the process of making the machine learning solution more general. The goal is to create a meta classifier. This meta-classifier has a better performance than the individual classifiers.

Each of the classification algorithms generates its predictions. This allows us to apply the majority votes principle and take the prediction that fits best.

Creating and Training¶

In [118]:
# Create a Voting Classifier
vot_clf = VotingClassifier(estimators=[('ada', ada_clf),('kNN',knn_clf)],voting='soft')

# Train Classifier
vot_clf.fit(X_train,y_train)

# Predict training data
y_vot_pred_train = vot_clf.predict(X_train)

# Predict testing data
y_vot_pred_test = vot_clf.predict(X_test)

# Model accuracy
print('Learned accuracy:')
print(accuracy_score(y_train, y_knn_pred_train))
print('Tested accuracy:')
print(accuracy_score(y_test, y_knn_pred_test))

0.7628865979381443

0.5958904109589042

Conclusion¶

Data¶

Most of the problems were caused by the LifeExpectancy dataset, because it was incomplete. For example, the USA lacked GDP and population. These data were however very important for the course of the project, since the USA played mostly at the front of the medal table. Beside the missing data, we dont completly trust the dataset. For example Estonia had some Years of really high and low Alcohol consumption.

Classifier¶

The work with the different Learner was however simpler. Python offers many possibilities and everything is documented in detail.

The accuracy of our learners are relatively good. In the confusion matrix we can see that the learners works well with a few medals. On higher medal counts however he is no longer so reliable. The reason for this is that most countries have not won any medals and only a few countries have won more than 30 Medals. As a result, the learner has too little data to make a reliable decision if he has won several medals.

Project¶

The MachineLearning project was very exciting because you could select the data set yourself. So you could choose a topic that you found interesting. With the Olympiad dataset we had a huge selection of possibilities.

We are satisfied with our project because we were able to apply and consolidate the content of the contact lesson and we got an acceptable result.

And we will win some Medals in the Future :D
